Interpretable Machine Learning: Shapley values

Karl Ho

2022-05-04

Prediction model for Taiwan presidential elections in 2016: predicting Tsai voters

Introduction

Machine learning models are not created for straignt-forward, easy interpretation in the first place. Predictive models from SVM, random forest, xgboost, deep learning give a certain prediction with accuracy rate but not explanable, not to mention the importance of individual features.

Recent research by Lundberg and Lee 2017 and Christoph Molner 2022 provides new techniques to interpret black-box models. One useful tool is Shapley values SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) developed by Scott M. Lundberg.

In an election model, for instance, a voter identifying as a supporter of DPP (Democratic Progressive Party in Taiwna) contributes certain percentage (say 17% ) of voting for Tsai while one identifying as Taiwanese (vs. Chinese) contributes 7%. Each variable had its contribution to the final percentage of predicting a vote for Tsai.

SHAP measures the impact of variables taking into account the interaction with other variables.

Shapley values calculate the importance of a feature by comparing what a model predicts with and without the feature. However, since the order in which a model sees features can affect its predictions, this is done in every possible order, so that the features are fairly compared.

Source: Gabriel Tseng. 2018. Interpreting complex models with SHAP values, Medium

# Plot Shapley values (SVM) using ggplot2

library(tidyverse)
ive_svmdf %>% 
  mutate(features=fct_reorder(features,attributions)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=attributions, y=features)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill = "steelblue") +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Shapley values (SVM)") + ylab("Features")

ive_rfdf=ive_rf
ive_rfdf$features=ive_rfdf$'_vname_'
ive_rfdf$attributions=ive_rfdf$'_attribution_'
# Creating attrib variable from ive objects
ive_rfdf$attrib =as.numeric(paste(ive_rfdf$'_sign_',ive_rfdf$attributions,sep=""))

# Plot Shapley values (Random Forest) using ggplot2
ive_rfdf %>% 
  mutate(features=fct_reorder(features,attrib)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=attributions, y=features)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill = "firebrick") +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Shapley values") + ylab("Features")

Interpreting the Shapley value plot?

  • The y-axis indicates the feature names, in order of importance from top to bottom.
  • On the x-axis is the Shapley value. Indicates how much is the change in probability of success in prediction.

Recommended readings about SHAP values

Start with Interpretable Machine Learning by Christoph Molnar. It addresses well theModel-Agnostic Methods and one of its particular cases Shapley values. An outstanding work.

Scott Lundberg’s work Interpretable Machine Learning with XGBoost also covers classical variable, ranking approaches like weight and gain, to shap values.
